Food debt to European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the euro area was the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 euro-zone countries, inflation was higher than expected in November - after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are only 3 percent, reported Bloomberg.
In contrast to the American, British, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the central rate. It is estimated that the interest rate reduction would favour the rise in raw materials prices and the slight fall in unemployment to the rise in inflation.
The ECB is striving to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in the spotlight: inflation should be "agreed" to exclude the need for action at a later stage.
At 3.3%, the inflation rate reached a record 12-year level in Germany in November, and in Spain the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1%.
The increase in inflation in the euro area was the result of an increase in food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat quotations increased by 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in food oil and milk products in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil increased by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached almost 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1% to 2.5% in 2008, but it is expected to fall to 1.9% in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3-percent inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to reduce interest rates twice.
