Many places are saved on disinfectants
More than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to inappropriate treatment of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overuse of beds, the overload of the staff - all factors that are not exactly conducive to the control of the infections, said the leading doctor of the National Epidemiology Centre.
Many places are also saved with the disinfectants.
In the trauma department of the János hospital, an MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed.
The bacterium resistant to antibiotics was found in a male patient who was hospitalised after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection.
The victim of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. Since then, an important operation could not be performed because of the bacterium that is still in the patient's body.
Until 10 December of this year, infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomalis Surveillance System from hospitals in 1094, according to the leading doctor of the National Epidemiology Centre, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been recorded in the hospitals with certainty, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by the MRSA, which is resistant to methicillin oxacillin to Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of the people in their nose without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as cervical inflammation, almond inflammation, skin inflammation or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well-healable.
However, if the means are too high or incorrectly used, the well-responding bacteria produce antibiotic resistant, which are rapidly spreading in the hospitals under appropriate conditions.
In particular, in patients with impaired, or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in elderly, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria may cause severe infections such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of the day-to-day disease.
You should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, told Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA only does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistance to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the care staff wears rubber gloves and masks in the supply, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - says Tibor Nyulasi.
When they are admitted to the hospital, patients are examined for MRSA, but an infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rare
The majority of the infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances are not favourable to the control of the emergence or spread of the multiresistant agent, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection is found mainly in hospitals and old-age homes, the hospital patients should examine the patients who have been brought in and isolate MRSA infected immediately.
However, in the Hungarian hospitals, microbiological sampling is not so common.
Not least because there are no subsidies from the State Health Insurance Fund for this investigation.
The majority of cases would therefore not be exposed until the patient had a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology centre.
For the European Union, there are strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotics therapies should be targeted, that is, microbiological studies are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug, but this directive is not always respected by hospitals.
Among the outpatient, or in the basic care, microbiological sampling was even more rare, said Karolina Böröcz.
In the case of disinfectants, it is saved
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most frequently transferred from one patient to another by the care staff.
This is why it is important to wash hands, or to wear gloves and masks, but there are also significant shortcomings in the hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in the home hospitals there is not always the possibility of isolating the infected patient.
The rooms are often overcrowded, the beds are close to each other, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina Böröcz continues to note, unfortunately, in the financially less well-placed hospitals, it even happens that disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that really favour the development of infections.
Such infections are shown to be far less common there, or the further spread of the agent can be stopped where these protective measures are observed, said Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections in control causes the health insurance huge costs, so they are being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA or its containment in the government programme has been maintained.
According to the first signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA), as well as the prevention of infections in hospitals as one of its priorities.
