Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
As Minister for the Environment Gábor Fodor announced, the meeting of experts will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the post-2012 emission reduction measures, i.e. after the Kyoto Protocol has expired.
A strong debate is currently under way between developed and developing countries.
The US has already signalled that they do not want to negotiate on concrete figures, but would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major question of the conference is whether the developed countries are prepared to support developing countries both financially and technologically, in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on support for developing countries has also been reached.
The adaptation fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, probably at the UN Global Environment Facility (GIF), as can be seen in the "Piac és Profit."
Hungary's six percent
Minister for the Environment, Gábor Fodor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU's commitment to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (measured by 1990 values), whether the "post-2012 agreement" is successful or not. The Union would even be prepared to support a 30% reduction, if other major developed countries in the world, or developing countries, are also ready to fully and responsibly meet their commitments.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the objective of the States that had joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2%, while the EU had already committed itself to a minus of 8% with its then 15 Member States.
The target for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to the years 1985-87 - a target that the country will fulfil, as can be seen in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The use is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly only come into force after 2012. In this case, the reduction project set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new international emission reduction system, the importance of which the IPCC, the UN's international scientific climate change committee, which was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize, has also highlighted in its recent report.
This would delay the reduction of emissions, and the increase in the average temperature of the earth by more than 2 ° C would be inevitable, which, according to scientists, would result in extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
British Army Recruits on YouTube
British Army units have published recordings of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase popularity on the video portal.
First of all, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: special units stationed in Afghanistan have been loading videos on the network for operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reports.
The images with the miniature cameras attached to helmets are checked at the Air Force Base in Kandahar and then sent to London where they are placed on the Internet.
Political message inevitable
Soldiers of the Air Force have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" was viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered under "defence headquarters" in spring 2007 to publish videos on Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Commonwealth Office) and the international peacekeeping forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq have their own YouTube channels.
Usage in Afghanistan
The Air Force originally published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defence says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual objectives of the foreign operations.
Such a kind of propaganda was almost free in comparison to traditional television advertising, so defence expert Gordon Mackenzie said to the BBC, but these videos always have a certain degree of political message, as they confirm in their own way the right to exist the military measures decided by the government.
Americans advertise with game
However, the army must also fight against amateur recordings, which, in addition to the carefully worked, censurized recordings, also make it into the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: in the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the maximum of the losses is spoken about, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
By the way, many videos of the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan have already been loaded to the platform, but the British have only recently discovered for themselves.
The Americans, however, are advertising in a slightly different way, that is, with the free-to-download "America's Army" shooting game, in which the player can slip into the soldier's skin as part of a more or less life-saving simulation.
