Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard established this August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary" have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
Among other things, the "risk warning report" of the Institute states that in the context of the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "strengthening of the existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic conflicts in the short term."
The main reason for this was the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is likely to be aimed at provocation of such a confrontation, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure by the political leaders: "People in public life have left the discussion of the Roma issue to representatives of radical political groups who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary opposition."
It is believed that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favour extremes, and increase the likelihood of violent conflicts.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention of the domestic and foreign media, "would have significantly damaged the image of Hungary abroad, in particular as regards confidence in stability and democratic maturity."
We remember that since autumn 2006, the reorganisation of radical and extremely right-wing groups in Hungary has been constantly in recovery, so that since summer 2007 several organisations, called the "national self-defence association," have been established.
"These groups are in common that they define themselves as a civil organisation, while they are openly boasting about preparing their members for, sometimes armed, defence tasks (civil protection, national defence, prevention of order), calling for the inadequacy of the police, the army, or the state itself," they said.
And on the other hand, all this is done in accordance with that method, which attempts to taunch various political aspirations based on the political and party defiance of the population as a bourgeois initiative.
The emphasis on the civil character and the form of the association therefore do not only serve to circumvent legal barriers that may arise in the course of the registration in court - it is also a political strategy.
The analysis shows that the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-raising factor for relations with the neighbouring countries.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, so some ultrationalist politicians of certain neighbouring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as the confirmation of its own anti-Hungary policy.
