A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidential treatment, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are located on a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, could not be seen until now, unless it was a humanitarian intention, that is, individual and name-related, that is, at the request of a former victim or his family.
The 11 States responsible for their administration, including Germany, France, Israel and the USA, agreed in May 2006 to make them available to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Harmful information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow research to be carried out, in particular through the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the health of the forced workers, Reto Masters, head of these archives, which are managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several countries, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public, due to the delicate nature of certain information.
Like, for example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The list of prisoners of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been gathered for a practical reason after the war: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and to provide them with any evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Today, in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent staff are working on tens of thousands of personal requests.
However, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
It is not to be expected that there will be any fundamental new news in these documents, as Pr. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Centre for Antisemitism of the Technical University of Berlin, had explained in 2006.
