New fears about the gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk of Russian exports from fuel to Western Europe being affected.
The majority of Russian gas exports to the European Union (EU) are led by Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is very closely observed.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge Russia for higher transit charges.
An earlier conflict between the two states last year reduced deliveries to the EU countries.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow is taking place at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian, state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine has to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be more calculated as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% additional for natural gas from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine has to pay 40% more for the imports of Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important guest transit states in talks," said the Minister for the Economy of Ukraine Anatoli Kinakh of the news agency Reuters.
"The changing gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments about the level of transit charges [to Western Europe] over Ukraine."
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006 Gazprom reduced deliveries to Ukraine.
This led to a case of exports to Western Europe, which dramatically increased prices.
Russian gas is a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Scottish State Health Service must improve the controls of the pre-criminal registers for workers from outside Europe, said a member of the control body.
The recommendation of the main financial controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was brought together in June with the attack on the Glasgow airport.
Black also expressed concerns that the Scottish State Health Service had no precise idea of the number of its foreign staff.
But his report pointed out that other important controls were carried out correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The main financial controller examined staff recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area as a result of the attack on Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a road car was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video transmission in October in the Old Bailey, and was charged with the alleged car bomb attack in the UK.
It is expected that the State Health Service will carry out checks prior to the employment of foreign employees to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorisations to work in the United Kingdom.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to check pre-trial registers, the Agency does not have the authority to obtain this information outside the UK.
The report of the main auditor now states, in addition to other recommendations, that the Board of Directors should take up guidelines for the exclusion of criminal records that help employers in controls in different countries.
"Although we have found evidence of these controls in some staff documents, they have not been routinely carried out." the report noted.
Black said that the Scottish health authorities would follow their investigation directives with a high degree of detail before the employment, but added: "Our report shows areas where the system can be improved to ensure that accurate information on the number of foreign health service workers is available."
BMA Scotland Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that prior to the deployment of potential NHS staff, investigations would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report says that current pre-appointment tests of the NHS Scotland are working well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say that they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of which are doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number was likely to be higher, also because the board of directors had problems identifying those employees who were left for an indefinite period of time.
The investigation continued to find that established control procedures were largely observed by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian.
These include passport, work permit and qualification checks.
the Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policy and guidelines for pre-employment controls for foreign staff in the NHS.
The health secretary Nicola Sturgeon said, "I was concerned to do this work in the face of the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport."
It added that the Scottish Government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that the best practices in updated guidelines on the control studies in the run-up to the employment of all employees, including those from abroad, are reflected in the publication of which is planned next month.
