They're not Warhol's boxes.
He who connects the terms Sweden and wooden box is thinking of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, wood boxes manufactured in Sweden throw dark shadows on Warhol's work directory.
Most of the 90 Brillo boxes of the "Type Stockholm" listed there are forgeries.
After a few months ago, the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes in 1968, internal research in the Moderna Museet in Stockholm is now coming to a good conclusion: the six "Brillo boxes" which the former museum director Pontus Hultén gave to the Moderna Museet in 1995 are copies - and probably the majority of the other hundred Brillo boxes of the "Stockholm type" which are in the international art market.
The history is entangled, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes," painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the paper cartons of the "Brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his work in the Moderna Museet 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - exhibited hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these were not from Warhol (for cost reasons), but were delivered directly from the Brillo Carton Factory.
These were not works of art, but their examples, just exhibits.
At the same time, in 1968, Warhol granted permission to produce a few glasses of wood in Sweden, which were not issued in the Moderna Museet.
Time witnesses are now talking about about about fifteen boxes, which at that time have rightly entered the art and auction history as authorized original Andy-Warhol-Brillo-Boxes called "Type Stockholm."
Some of them have achieved more than $100 000 on auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that in 1968 about a hundred wooden boxes were produced and issued in Sweden, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, it was not until 1990 that Hulténs 105 boxes were produced in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol was dead for three years.
Lars Byström, head conservatory at Moderna Museet, has also studied three of the Swedish private property, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press panels were first ground and milled, then white oil was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the color was applied directly to the press plate with a painting roll without a foundation - and it is not about oil, but about acrylic.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," says the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve, "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in his collection as copies / exhibition material."
In July, however, the Authentication Board announced that it would follow the "serious accusations" that are made in the case of the soap powder boxes.
But ever since then, it has been kept in an inexorable silence.
